<b>Research Interests</b><p>

My major areas of research are artificial intelligence, biomedical and
health informatics, and the societal impact of computers, especially
in health and historical analysis. In biomedical and health
informatics I am working on models for representing underlying
knowledge in clinical records and guidelines, on methods of medical
clinical support, biomedical imaging and predictive data mining, and
on the history of biomedical and health informatics. In artificial
intelligence, my concentration is on pattern recognition, clustering,
expert problem solving and knowledge representation, and visual
reasoning. In imaging it is on clustering and segmentation in large
scale image sets, and on the annotation of clinical images within the 
context of clinical problem-solving using metaphor and language in novel ways. 
On societal impact, I am investigating the effects
of computer technology on medical practice, biomedical research,
bioethics, and the history of informatics and its impact on clinical care.
 
